codex
Findings:

The robustness claim is directionally supported, but the table underserves the claim. Since the prose argues `17/18` winning-domain cells beat the strongest baseline, the table should expose both Llama-vs-base and Mistral-vs-base deltas or rank flags. As written, only Mistral’s delta is shown, so the reader must manually verify Llama wins and the Books miss.

The Books near-miss is handled honestly: `0.2710` vs `0.2737` is correctly reported as about `-1.0%`, and the text does not round it into a win. That said, calling the result “rank-1 NDCG@10” later is risky because Llama is not rank-1 on Books; qualify it as “near-universal rank-1 across winning domains” or “17/18 cells.”

Beauty/Movies are also handled mostly rigorously. The text explicitly says Qwen is not first and that both added backbones remain below the strongest baseline. This avoids overclaiming. The phrase “full pattern of six wins and two losses transfers” is acceptable only if “pattern” means domain-level win/loss partition, not exact ranks or effect sizes, since the added backbones are much weaker on Movies and Beauty.

Main skeptic objection: this is still a robustness test of the scoring backbone inside C-CRP, not full external validity of the method under alternative backbone-tuned protocols. The strongest baselines appear fixed, presumably from Qwen-aligned official comparisons, while C-CRP changes backbone. That is fine if framed as “C-CRP’s posterior signal remains competitive under frozen-model substitution,” but too strong if framed as a general cross-backbone SOTA result. Also, “absolute level tracks backbone quality” is asserted, not evidenced; table shows Qwen highest in all rows, but does not establish model quality as the cause.

SCORE_BACKBONE: 8/10

Single most important fix: add Llama-vs-base deltas/rank markers to the table and soften “rank-1 result” language to explicitly allow the Books miss and Beauty/Movies losses.
